Urban Infrastructure & Public Safety

Dataset: Road.csv

Description:
Traffic accidents are rarely caused by a single factor; they are the tragic result of intersecting variables ranging from road conditions and lighting to driver experience and vehicle defects. Teams are tasked with building a robust predictive system capable of forecasting the Accident_severity (Slight Injury, Serious Injury, etc.) based on post-crash report data. This challenge requires navigating complex, messy, real-world categorical data to find the signal in the noise.

What Teams Will Build:
A deep-dive categorical analysis pinpointing the primary catalysts for severe accidents.
A robust Multi-Class Classification model predicting the severity of the accident.
A strategic data-driven proposal for local traffic authorities detailing the top 3 infrastructural or policy changes needed to reduce "Serious Injuries".

Data Science Components:
Advanced Categorical Encoding: Transforming heavy text-based features (Weather conditions, Road alignment, Vehicle types) into machine-readable formats using techniques like Target Encoding or One-Hot Encoding.
Imbalance Handling: Applying techniques (like SMOTE, class weighting, or undersampling) to deal with the natural class imbalance of accident severity.
Evaluation Metrics: Focus strictly on Macro and Micro F1-Scores and Confusion Matrices, as raw accuracy will be misleading due to class distribution.

Learning Outcomes:
Mastering advanced preprocessing for high-cardinality text columns.
Combating severe class imbalance in real-world operational data.
Deriving high-level policy and infrastructure insights from granular event logs.

Real-World Application:
Empowers smart-city infrastructure grids to dynamically allocate emergency response resources and helps policymakers prioritize specific road redesigns based on empirical hazard data.
